nd has now become a kitsch tourist destination famed for its colonial villas, flower beds, pristine lakes, and pastoral landscapes. Eric T. Jennings finds that from its very beginning, Dalat embodied the paradoxes of colonialism—it was a city of leisure built on the backs of thousands of coolies, a supposed paragon of hygiene that offered only questionable protection from disease, and a new venture into ethnic relations that ultimately backfired. Jennings’ fascinating history opens a new window onto virtually all aspects of French Indochina, from architecture and urban planning to violence, labor, métissage, health and medicine, gender and ethic relations, schooling, religion, comportments, anxieties, and more.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aasia scholars.  aasian history.  aasian studies.  acolonial historians.  acolonial villas.  acolonialism.  acultural anthropology.  acultural historians.  acultural perspective.  adalat.  aethnic relations.  aethnographers.  aethnography.  aeurope.  afrench empire.  afrench indochina.  agender relations.  ahealth and medicine.  ahistorians.  aimperialism.  anonfiction.  apolitical science.  apostcolonialism.  aregional history.  asouthern vietnam.  atourist destination.  aworld history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026659940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094844040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520948440423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520948440/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY